{"id":"1705.03651","submitter":"Michal Kolar","authors":"M. Kol\\'a\\v{r}, A. Ryabov, and R. Filip","title":"Extracting work from quantum states of radiation","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 93, 063822 (2016)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.93.063822","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum optomechanics opens a possibility to mediate a physical connection of\nquantum optics and classical thermodynamics. We propose and theoretically\nanalyze a one-way chain starting from various quantum states of radiation. In\nthe chain, the radiation state is first ideally swapped to sufficiently large\nmechanical oscillator (membrane). Then the membrane mechanically pushes a\nclassical almost mass-less piston, which is pressing a gas in a small\ncontainer. As a result we observe strongly nonlinear and nonmonotonic transfer\nof the energy stored in classical and quantum uncertainty of radiation to\nmechanical work. The amount of work and even its sign depends strongly on the\nuncertainty of the radiation state. Our theoretical prediction would stimulate\nan experimental proposals for such optomechanical connection to thermodynamics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 10 May 2017 08:16:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-05-11"}
